    "# SortSmart: Deep Learning Waste Classification for Mobile and Industrial Deployment\n\n## README \u2014 How to Run This Notebook\n\n### Quick Start\n1. **Dataset:** Download the [RealWaste dataset](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/joebeachcapital/realwaste) from Kaggle.\n2. **Extract** so that the folder contains 9 subfolders (one per class): `Cardboard/`, `Food Organics/`, `Glass/`, etc.\n3. **Set path:**\n   - **Google Colab:** Upload to Google Drive at `/content/drive/MyDrive/RealWaste/` (auto-detected).\n   - **VS Code / Local:** Place the `RealWaste/` folder next to this notebook.\n4. **Run:** Press **\"Run All\"** in VS Code or Colab. All dependencies install automatically in Cell 1.\n\n### Environment\n- **Python:** 3.11 or 3.12 (3.13+ not supported by current PyTorch wheels)\n- **GPU:** NVIDIA T4 or equivalent (tested on Colab T4 with 15 GB VRAM)\n- **Runtime:** ~45\u201360 minutes on T4 GPU with mixed precision enabled\n\n### Project Structure\n| File | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `SortSmart_Notebook.ipynb` | Main notebook (this file) \u2014 contains all code, outputs, and documentation |\n| `report.pdf` | Critical reflection report (Part 2 of the assessment) |\n\n### Requirements (auto-installed)\n`torch`, `torchvision`, `timm`, `albumentations`, `scikit-learn`, `matplotlib`, `seaborn`, `Pillow`, `tqdm`, `numpy`, `opencv-python-headless`\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nThis project addresses the real-world problem of **automated waste material classification** by comparing three deep learning architectures across a **mobile-to-industrial deployment spectrum** on the **RealWaste** dataset (Single et al., 2023).\n\nThese architectures were **not evaluated in the original RealWaste paper**, which tested VGG-16, InceptionResNetV2, DenseNet121, Inception V3, and MobileNetV2 (best: 89.19%). This project extends that work with newer architectures.\n\n### Models & Results\n\n| Model | Test Accuracy | F1-Score | Params | Size | Target Deployment |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Baseline CNN (scratch) | 33.61% | 31.73% | ~1.2M | ~4.6 MB | Reference only |\n| EfficientNet-B0 (2019) | 73.11% | 73.17% | ~4.0M | ~15.3 MB | Mobile app |\n| **ConvNeXt-Tiny (2022)** | **94.12%** | **94.24%** | ~27.8M | ~106.2 MB | MRF / industrial edge |\n| *Paper best: Inception V3* | *89.19%* | *90.25%* | *~24M* | *~96 MB* | *Single et al. (2023)* |\n\nConvNeXt-Tiny surpasses the paper's best result by **+4.93 percentage points**.\n\n### Dataset\n- **RealWaste** \u2014 4,752 images, 9 classes, captured from a real landfill (Whyte Gully, Australia)\n- **Licence:** CC BY-NC-SA 4.0\n- **Source:** https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/joebeachcapital/realwaste\n- **Paper:** Single, S., Iranmanesh, S. & Raad, R. (2023). *Information*, 14(12), 633.\n- **Classes:** Cardboard, Food Organics, Glass, Metal, Miscellaneous Trash, Paper, Plastic, Textile Trash, Vegetation\n\n### Notebook Sections\n1. Environment Setup\n2. Dataset Loading & Auto-Detection\n3. Exploratory Data Analysis\n4. Data Preprocessing (stratified split, augmentation, class weighting)\n5. Training & Evaluation Utilities (with mixed precision)\n6. Model 1: Baseline CNN (from scratch)\n7. Model 2: EfficientNet-B0 (transfer learning, two-phase fine-tuning)\n8. Model 3: ConvNeXt-Tiny (transfer learning, two-phase fine-tuning)\n9. Final Comparison (metrics table + charts)\n10. Grad-CAM Interpretability\n11. Deployment Profiling (params, size, inference time)\n12. Summary & Future Work"
   ]
