    "## 4. Data Preprocessing\n",
    "\n",
    "**Split:** 80% train / 10% validation / 10% test (stratified to preserve class proportions).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Resolution:** 224\u00d7224 \u2014 reduced from the paper's 524\u00d7524 for mobile efficiency. This is a deliberate trade-off: lower resolution reduces accuracy slightly but is necessary for real-time mobile inference. EfficientNet-B0 was designed for 224\u00d7224 input (Tan & Le, 2019).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Augmentation strategy \u2014 research-informed:**\n",
    "- **Geometric augmentations (primary):** RandomResizedCrop, horizontal flip, rotation (\u00b120\u00b0), shear (15\u00b0), translation. Geometric transforms are proven superior to photometric for waste classification (Shijie et al., 2017; de la Rosa et al., 2022). Single et al. (2023) used flip + elastic distortion + rotation + shear.\n",
    "- **Photometric augmentations (secondary):** ColorJitter (brightness, contrast, saturation, hue), GaussianBlur, RandomGrayscale. These simulate lighting variation across different environments (kitchen, outdoor bin, MRF conveyor).\n",
    "- **Occlusion simulation:** RandomErasing (10%) simulates partial occlusion from overlapping items in bins \u2014 related to Cutout regularisation (DeVries & Taylor, 2017).\n",
    "- **ImageNet normalisation:** Required for compatibility with pretrained EfficientNet and ConvNeXt weights.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Class imbalance:** Plastic (831 images) vs Textile Trash (286 images) = 2.9x ratio. Addressed with inverse-frequency weighted cross-entropy loss and weighted random sampling."
   ]
