    "## 8. Model 3: ConvNeXt-Tiny \u2014 MRF / Industrial Deployment Target\n",
    "\n",
    "**ConvNeXt-Tiny** (Liu et al., 2022) is a pure CNN **redesigned using Vision Transformer principles**. This was **not tested in the original RealWaste paper**.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why Tiny specifically (not Small, Base, or Large)?**\n",
    "- **Overfitting prevention:** ConvNeXt-Small (50M params) and Base (89M params) would massively overfit on ~4,800 images. Tiny at 28.6M params is already large \u2014 mitigated by progressive fine-tuning and early stopping.\n",
    "- **Realistic MRF deployment:** At ~114 MB and 4.5B FLOPs, Tiny runs on industrial edge hardware like NVIDIA Jetson Xavier (~10 TOPS). Small/Base/Large would require a full GPU server, unrealistic for most MRF conveyor systems.\n",
    "- **Sufficient capacity:** 9-class waste classification does not need the capacity of ConvNeXt-Base (designed for 1000-class ImageNet). Tiny provides more than enough representational power.\n",
    "- **Literature precedent:** Qi et al. (2023) used ConvNeXt for waste classification on ~1,660 images. Tanvir et al. (2025) achieved 94.97% with ConvNeXt on TrashNeXt.\n",
    "- **Clear deployment spectrum:** EfficientNet-B0 (5.3M, 21 MB, mobile) vs ConvNeXt-Tiny (28.6M, 114 MB, industrial) \u2014 a meaningful accuracy-efficiency trade-off, not a trivial comparison.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What makes ConvNeXt architecturally novel \u2014 ViT design principles in a CNN:**\n",
    "- **7\u00d77 depthwise convolutions:** Larger receptive field, analogous to ViT patch embeddings (vs standard 3\u00d73)\n",
    "- **GELU activation:** Smoother than ReLU, borrowed from Transformers\n",
    "- **Layer Normalisation:** Replaces BatchNorm, as used in Transformers\n",
    "- **Inverted bottleneck blocks:** Fewer activation and normalisation layers \u2014 sparse design inspired by Transformer FFN blocks\n",
    "- **Patchify stem:** 4\u00d74 non-overlapping convolution (like ViT patch embedding), replacing the traditional stem\n",
    "\n",
    "Recent waste studies confirm ConvNeXt's strength: Tanvir et al. (2025) \u2014 94.97% on TrashNeXt; Madhavi et al. (2025) \u2014 ConvNeXt-V1 best at 96.95% across 14 pretrained CNNs; Yevle & Mann (2025) \u2014 SwinConvNeXt achieving 98.97%.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Training strategy:** Same two-phase progressive fine-tuning as EfficientNet-B0."
