    "## 12. Summary\n\n### Key Findings\n\n| Model | Accuracy | F1-Score | Params | Size | Inference (CPU) | Deployment |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Baseline CNN | 33.61% | 31.73% | 1.2M | 4.6 MB | 72.8 ms | Reference only |\n| EfficientNet-B0 | 73.11% | 73.17% | 4.0M | 15.3 MB | 39.8 ms | **Mobile app** \u2713 |\n| ConvNeXt-Tiny | **94.12%** | **94.24%** | 27.8M | 106.2 MB | 147.5 ms | **MRF server** \u2713 |\n| *Paper: Inception V3* | *89.19%* | *90.25%* | *~24M* | *~96 MB* | *\u2014* | *Single et al. (2023)* |\n\n### Observations\n\n1. **Transfer learning is essential**: The baseline CNN (trained from scratch on ~3,800 images) achieved only 33.61%, confirming that ImageNet pretraining is critical when data is limited. EfficientNet-B0 and ConvNeXt-Tiny, both initialised with ImageNet weights, achieved 73.11% and 94.12% respectively \u2014 demonstrating the value of learned feature representations for waste classification.\n\n2. **ConvNeXt-Tiny surpasses the paper's best result**: At 94.12% accuracy (vs. Inception V3's 89.19%), ConvNeXt-Tiny demonstrates that its ViT-inspired design principles \u2014 7\u00d77 depthwise convolutions, GELU activation, and LayerNorm \u2014 provide meaningful improvements over earlier architectures on this dataset.\n\n3. **Deployment spectrum**: No single model fits all scenarios. EfficientNet-B0 (15.3 MB, 39.8 ms) is deployable on mobile phones for consumer waste sorting apps. ConvNeXt-Tiny (106.2 MB, 147.5 ms) is suited for industrial MRF conveyor systems where accuracy takes priority over model size.\n\n4. **Challenging classes**: Grad-CAM analysis reveals that Miscellaneous Trash remains the hardest class (F1: 87.5%) due to its diverse visual feature space. Glass achieved the highest F1 (98.8%), likely due to distinctive transparency and reflective properties. Confusion between cardboard/paper and plastic/glass mirrors findings from Single et al. (2023).\n\n### Future Work\n- **Knowledge distillation**: Compress ConvNeXt-Tiny (teacher) into an EfficientNet-sized student model to bridge the accuracy-efficiency gap \u2014 preliminary experiments showed promising results with the student reaching ~88% validation accuracy before the Colab session limit was reached.\n- **MRF scaling**: Deploy the classification model on conveyor belt cameras with real-time inference for automated industrial sorting.\n- **UK-specific fine-tuning**: Retrain on UK waste composition data to address the geographic bias of the Australian RealWaste dataset.\n- **Vision Transformer exploration**: Evaluate DeiT-Small or Swin-Tiny to extend the CNN-Transformer comparison.\n\n"
